    "## Codespace for Checkpoint 1"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## `Optimize` Module\n",
    "### Example 1: Stellar Hotspots\n",
    "As with any area of science, we fit models to data. `Scipy` has an `optimize` package which provides a host of fitting routines that allow for least-squares regression for non-linear fits. This section covers the most useful function, `curve_fit`, which allows fitting nonlinear functions.\n",
    "\n",
    "Run the cell below to get started:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "import scipy.optimize as opt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from matplotlib import pyplot as plt\n",
    "## Lists to store data\n",
    "time = []\n",
    "flux = []\n",
    "flux_err = []\n",
    "\n",
    "## Parameters to base our data on\n",
    "amp1 = 0.04\n",
    "amp2 = 0.06\n",
    "freq = 30\n",
    "freq2 = 25\n",
    "for index in range(200):\n",
    "    index = index/200\n",
    "    time.append(index)\n",
    "    flux.append(((amp1)*np.sin(freq*index) +(amp2)*np.sin(freq2*index)) + np.random.normal(1, scale=0.01))\n",
    "    flux_err.append(0.01)\n",
    "    \n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's begin by plotting our data above:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "plt.errorbar(time, flux, yerr=flux_err, ecolor='black', elinewidth=0.75, marker='o', linestyle='', markersize=4)\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Time (Days)')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Flux')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Signals similar to this can appear in photometric data. They occur due to the rotation of hotspots on the stellar surface. Since the spots are cooler than the rest of the star, the observed flux fluctuates with the period of the star. Multiple hotspots can coexist, leading to patterns as seen above. Stars also exhibit **differential rotation**, where the star will rotate faster at the equator than at higher or lower latitudes, which can cause the hotspots to rotate at slightly different periods. A **simple** model of hotspots can be achieved by a sum of sines:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$ F(t) = \\Sigma^{n}_{i=0} ({A_{i}\\sin{(\\omega_{i}t + \\phi_{i})} + A_{i+1}\\sin{(\\omega_{i+1}t + \\phi_{i+1})}\\cdots})$$\n",
    "where $A$ is the amplitude in flux change due to the hotspot ($\\propto$ spot area relative to the surface), $\\omega$ is the rotation speed of the star at the hot spot's latitude, and $\\phi$ is the phase offset of the hotspots with respect to stellar longitude. Typically, these signals are more robustly modeled and subtracted using the Lomb-Scargle Periodogram (a Fourier Series), which is supported by the `astropy` module. For this simple example, we will model them using `scipy`.\n",
    "\n",
    "When searching for transit signals, baseline trends (or 'red noise') caused by stellar activity need to be removed. We will use `curve_fit` for this example to derive values for $A$ and $\\omega$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Create the model to fit\n",
    "def double_sine(t, a1, a2, w1, w2, b):\n",
    "    return a1*np.sin(w1*t) + a2*np.sin(w2*t) + b\n",
    "\n",
    "## To call curve fit, pass the function above along with your data\n",
    "popt, pcov = opt.curve_fit(double_sine, time, flux, p0=[0.03, 0.02, 30, 30, 1], absolute_sigma=flux_err, maxfev=10000)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(popt)\n",
    "## Extract the fitted parameters\n",
    "print('A1 is ' + str(popt[0]))\n",
    "print('A2 is ' + str(popt[1]))\n",
    "print('w1 is ' + str(popt[2]))\n",
    "print('w2 is ' + str(popt[3]))\n",
    "print('b is ' + str(popt[4]))\n",
    "x = np.linspace(0,1, num=1000)\n",
    "plt.errorbar(time, flux, yerr=flux_err, ecolor='black', elinewidth=0.75, marker='o', linestyle='', markersize=4, zorder=-11, label='Data')\n",
    "plt.plot(x, double_sine(x, popt[0], popt[1], popt[2], popt[3], popt[4]), linestyle='--', color='red', label='Model')\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Rel. Flux')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Time (days)')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Example 2: Stellar Flares\n",
    "Stellar flares are eruptions of plasma and photons occurring at the surface of a star due to the reconnection of magnetic field lines. These manifest in photometry as a **sudden increase in brightness** that decays, usually exponentially, over a few minutes to a couple of hours. We will import real TESS photometry of a flare on [Proxima Centauri](https://www.aanda.org/articles/aa/full_html/2022/02/aa42337-21/aa42337-21.html), which has three known exoplanets."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "from matplotlib import pyplot as plt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "data = pd.read_csv(\"../../Auxiliary_Files/Data/Data_Structures/Prox_Cen.csv\")\n",
    "time = data['time']\n",
    "rel_flux = data['Normalized_Flux']\n",
    "flux_err = data['error']\n",
    "plt.scatter(time, rel_flux, s = 0.75)\n",
    "plt.title(\"Flare on Proxima Centauri\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(\"Rel. Flux\")\n",
    "plt.xlabel(\"Time (BJD - 2457000)\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Closely examined, we can see the flare actually has two outbursts; flares can occur in outbursts, so it is not uncommon to see multiple decay profiles in one event. In this case, however, we will only consider the last decay profile, which is the most prominent here. To model the flare, we will adopt the following model for the decay profile:\n",
    "$$ F(t) = a \\exp{[-b(t - t_{0})]} + c$$\n",
    "where $a$ is the amplitude of the flare, $t_{0}$ is the temportal offset of the flare peak, and $c$ is the flux offset. Implementing this in Python:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "def exp_decay(x, A, t0, D):\n",
    "    return A*np.exp(-t0*x) + D\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Since we only want to model the data *after* the peak of the flare, we want to splice the time and data starting at the peak. We can do this using the `np.argmax` function:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Reimport so that we can rerun the block as many times as we need\n",
    "data = pd.read_csv(\"../../Auxiliary_Files/Data/Data_Structures/Prox_Cen.csv\")\n",
    "time = data['time']\n",
    "rel_flux = data['Normalized_Flux']\n",
    "flux_err = data['error']\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "## Splice the data so that we begin at the flare peak\n",
    "idx = np.argmax(rel_flux)\n",
    "time = time[idx:] - time[idx]\n",
    "rel_flux = rel_flux[idx:]\n",
    "flux_err = flux_err[idx:]\n",
    "\n",
    "## Run curve_fit to estimate the best fit parameters. We can estimate some of the parameters by eye\n",
    "popt, pcov = opt.curve_fit(exp_decay, time, rel_flux,p0=[0.03, 1, 0.998],maxfev=10000)\n",
    "plt.errorbar(time, rel_flux, yerr=flux_err,ecolor='black', elinewidth=0.4, marker='o', linestyle='', markersize=1.5, zorder=-11, label='Data')\n",
    "plt.plot(time, exp_decay(time, popt[0],popt[1],popt[2]))\n",
    "plt.title('Model of Proxima Centauri Flare')\n",
    "plt.xlabel(\"Time Since Peak (Days)\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(\"Rel. Flux\")"
   ]
  }
 ],
